<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Aspergillaceae" genus="Penicillium" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Penicillium vaccaeorum" order="Eurotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="vaccaeorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Penicillium vaccaeorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. lacussarmientei" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="lacussarmientei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. lacussarmientei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, two species described from sandy soils in Spain and Chile (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00641181" author="Quintanilla, JA" journalOrPublisher="Mycopathologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="73 - 82" refId="B68" refString="Quintanilla, JA, 1982. Three new species of Penicillium isolated from soil. Mycopathologia 80: 73 - 82, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00641181" title="Three new species of Penicillium isolated from soil." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00641181" volume="80" year="1982">Quintanilla 1982</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00467682" author="Ramirez, C" journalOrPublisher="Mycopathologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="29 - 32" refId="B69" refString="Ramirez, C, 1986. A new species of Penicillium from the Chilean Tierra del Fuego. Mycopathologia 96: 29 - 32, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00467682" title="A new species of Penicillium from the Chilean Tierra del Fuego." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00467682" volume="96" year="1986">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ramírez">Ramirez</normalizedToken>
1986
</bibRefCitation>
), respectively, were considered synonyms of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. roseopurpureum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="roseopurpureum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. roseopurpureum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Frisvad, JC" journalOrPublisher="Persoonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="209 - 232" refId="B16" refString="Frisvad, JC, Samson, RA, Stolk, AC, 1990. Disposition of recently described species of Penicillium. Persoonia 14: 209 - 232" title="Disposition of recently described species of Penicillium." volume="14" year="1990">Frisvad et al. (1990)</bibRefCitation>
, noting that both species were fast growing variants of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. roseopurpureum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="roseopurpureum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. roseopurpureum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Later on, based on that criterion and the lack of morphological differences, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" author="Houbraken, J" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="53 - 138" refId="B34" refString="Houbraken, J, Frisvad, JC, Samson, RA, 2011. Taxonomy of Penicillium section Citrina. Studies in Mycology 70: 53 - 138, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" title="Taxonomy of Penicillium section Citrina." url="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" volume="70" year="2011">Houbraken et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
considered the two former species synonyms of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. sanguifluum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="sanguifluum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. sanguifluum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
despite some sequence variation where 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. vaccaeorum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="vaccaeorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. vaccaeorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. lacussarmientei" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="lacussarmientei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. lacussarmientei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clustered together in a clade sister to that of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. sanguifluum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="sanguifluum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. sanguifluum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Our phylogeny correlates with 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" author="Houbraken, J" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="53 - 138" refId="B34" refString="Houbraken, J, Frisvad, JC, Samson, RA, 2011. Taxonomy of Penicillium section Citrina. Studies in Mycology 70: 53 - 138, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" title="Taxonomy of Penicillium section Citrina." url="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" volume="70" year="2011">Houbraken et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
who found the same topology. Having the opportunity to examine specimens from both monophyletic sister clades (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Phylogenetic tree of Penicillium section Citrina based on ML analysis obtained by RAxML inferred from the combined tub 2, cmdA, and ITS loci. Branch lengths are proportional to phylogenetic distance. Bootstrap support values / Bayesian posterior probability scores above 70 % / 0.95 are indicated on the nodes. Bold branches indicate bs / pp values 100 / 1. The tree is rooted to P. cainii DAOM 239914 and P. jacksonii CCFC 239937. The name in green is the resurrected species P. vaccaeorum included in this study. T = Ex-type strain." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.86.73861.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/640607" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">8</figureCitation>
), we observed consistent phenotypic features to distinguish them. For instance, isolates of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. vaccaeorum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="vaccaeorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. vaccaeorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had longer stipes (up to 103 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
; up to 120 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in the protologue of the species) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00641181" author="Quintanilla, JA" journalOrPublisher="Mycopathologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="73 - 82" refId="B68" refString="Quintanilla, JA, 1982. Three new species of Penicillium isolated from soil. Mycopathologia 80: 73 - 82, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00641181" title="Three new species of Penicillium isolated from soil." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00641181" volume="80" year="1982">Quintanilla 1982</bibRefCitation>
), they were able to grow on CYA at 35 °C (6-11 mm diam. after 7 d), had good sporulation and faster growth on YES agar (30-32 mm diam. 7 d) and more restricted on DG18 (12-13 mm diam. 7 d). In contrast, isolates of the 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. sanguifluum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="sanguifluum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. sanguifluum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade showed considerably shorter conidiophores (15-50 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long), they were unable to grow above 30 °C, and the colonies on YES and DG18 showed sparsely or absent sporulation and attained 18-28 mm and 16-22 mm diam., respectively (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" author="Houbraken, J" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="53 - 138" refId="B34" refString="Houbraken, J, Frisvad, JC, Samson, RA, 2011. Taxonomy of Penicillium section Citrina. Studies in Mycology 70: 53 - 138, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" title="Taxonomy of Penicillium section Citrina." url="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.70.02" volume="70" year="2011">Houbraken et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Hence, genetic and phenotypic differences support the reinstatement of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. vaccaeorum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="vaccaeorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. vaccaeorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as an accepted species, with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. lacussarmientei" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="lacussarmientei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. lacussarmientei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
considered synonym. This species together with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. sanguifluum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="sanguifluum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. sanguifluum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. roseopurpureum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="roseopurpureum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. roseopurpureum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are classified in series 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="series" series="Roseopurpurea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Roseopurpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which differs from almost all series of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Citrina" genus="P." lsidName="subsp. section" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="section" section="Citrina" species="roseopurpureum" subSpecies="section">section Citrina</taxonomicName>
by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="species’">species'</normalizedToken>
monoverticillate conidiophores. The only other series in the section with monoverticillate conidiophores is 
<taxonomicName genus="Gallaica" lsidName="Gallaica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Gallaica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, represented exclusively by 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. gallaicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="gallaicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. gallaicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which differs from the former series mainly by the production of sclerotia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.05.002" author="Houbraken, J" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="5 - 169" refId="B39" refString="Houbraken, J, Kocsube, S, Visagie, CM, Yilmaz, N, Wang, XC, Meijer, M, Kraak, B, Hubka, V, Bensch, K, Samson, RA, Frisvad, JC, 2020. Classification of Aspergillus, Penicillium, Talaromyces and related genera (Eurotiales): an overview of families, genera, subgenera, sections, series and species. Studies in Mycology 95: 5 - 169, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.05.002" title="Classification of Aspergillus, Penicillium, Talaromyces and related genera (Eurotiales): an overview of families, genera, subgenera, sections, series and species." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.05.002" volume="95" year="2020">Houbraken et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
According to the revised data, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. vaccaeorum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="vaccaeorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. vaccaeorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs worldwide, and is commonly isolated from sandy soils of beaches and forests, and even associated with ants (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Strain information and GenBank / EMBL accession numbers of the Penicillium species investigated in this study." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/9C0C60DB40FE68D5F623FDDA35382CFD" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" tableUuid="9C0C60DB40FE68D5F623FDDA35382CFD">1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
